From: kestrel@selway.umt.edu (Christopher J Dewey)
Subject: Re: Linux Community Divided ? (was: Linux counter)
Date: Sat, 23 Oct 1993 19:30:53 GMT

In article <CFBH65.MEF@sybase.com>, Nitin Borwankar <nitin@sybase.com> wrote:
>
>It seems to me that the Linux community consists of a number of
>segments.  All the segments want Linux to be successful.
>On this point there is unison.
> 
>However there appear to be a number of different agendas, and if
>these are not seen early, we could all be at odds, much like the
>multiple commercial Un*x vendors.

[example agendas list deleted]

>Some of these don't bother the large Systems Admin's and their bosses.
>But some others do. If Linux is to be successful in drawing commercial
>software developers ( I work for one such large company  ) there's
>got to be something in it for them - giving away source is something they're
>not used to.

Allow me to introduce myself as a U*ix novice and and utter Linux newbie.
After having allowed myself to be held captive by the dominant PC marketing
establishment, I have experienced epiphany.  I have seen the Light, and the
Light is Linux.  My very first impression of Linux is that it is very much
geared towards the end-user.  If Linus had truly worried about what's "in
it for them" we would not be here discussing such matters.

>So the Linux community probably needs to consider what our feelings are
>on binary-only software products on Linux.  If this is something we 
>welcome, then it's only a matter of a year or two ( my opinion )
>before Linux takes off as a commercial platform.  If we ( through
>copylefts, etc. ) insist that every *app* developed on Linux also
>come with source. Linux will take much longer to take off as a 
>commercial software platform. 

Do we want Linux to "take off as a commercial platform"?  Linux strikes
me as being the platform with the "in your face" attitude toward commercial
developers.  I see Linux as the philosophical refuge for those dedicated
to development, not those dedicated to the almighty dollar.  Do you think
Bill Gates would help the Linux cause?

>It appears that there may be many differing views on this and
>perhaps this may be a good time and place to discuss what we feel about
>this.  I'm sure some interesting discussions will emerge.

I'm looking forward to following this thread myself.  There are some
really big philosophical issues to be dealt with here.   Linuxers have
to consider their motives along with their desires.  We have to ask why
Linux is attractive as well as how to make it even more so.

>My own personal opinion is that if we invite commercial binary-only
>apps on Linux, we will already have created strong competition to
>binary-only Un*x vendors. And this will go a long way in the direction
>of the original GNU manifesto of free sharing of code.
>So, a step at a time and let's welcome copyright apps on top
>off copyleft Linux. My personal opinion only.
>Nitin Borwankar.

Yours is a very sensible opinion, Nitin (IMHO, of course).  I am a week
old to this concept of a freely available OS and development platform.
I wouldn't like to lose that most important quality.  The very idea that
Linux evolved from a very loosely knit group of developers into a stable
and powerful package was enough to convert me.  Linux is also not such a
clique that somebody can't join in.  It's sort of like a "socialist OS"
if you will.  And by God, it works!

I'd like to see it hit the real mainstream, simply because Linux thrives
on its users; however, most strategies to introduce it to the mainstream
PC population include marketing techniques which could be harmful to the
very spirit of Linux.  You are no doubt correct to assume that Linux would
become very popular very quickly if commercial binaries are welcomed, but
fast growth does not come without growing pains.

Instead, I think it would be best if Linux continues to expand the way
it has so far:  one user at a time.  And I am one of the latest.

Christopher Dewey
kestrel@selway.umt.edu
cdewey@doc.helios.nd.edu

